  "nursesNote": "Motivational interviewing (MI) is a collaborative, patient-centered way to strengthen a person's own motivation and commitment to change, useful in substance use and other behavior change. The nurse expresses empathy nonjudgmentally, helps the patient see the discrepancy between current behavior and their own goals, rolls with resistance instead of arguing or confronting, and supports self-efficacy (the belief they can change). Core skills are OARS: Open-ended questions, Affirmations, Reflective listening, and Summarizing. The nurse draws out the patient's own reasons for change (change talk) rather than lecturing or jumping in to fix the problem (the 'righting reflex'). The patient's autonomy is respected: the patient decides, and the nurse guides without forcing. This approach lowers defensiveness and increases readiness to change.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Use a collaborative, nonjudgmental approach",
    "Express empathy and support self-efficacy",
    "Help the patient see discrepancy with their own goals",
    "Roll with resistance; do not argue or lecture",
    "Use OARS and draw out the patient's own reasons to change"
  ],
